-*- Text -*-
This is the file .../info/dir, which contains the topmost node of the
Info hierarchy.  The first time you invoke Info you start off
looking at that node, which is (dir)Top.

File: dir	Node: Top	This is the top of the INFO tree

The Info Directory
******************

  The Info Directory is the top-level menu of major Info topics.
  Type "d" in Info to return to the Info Directory.  Type "q" to exit Info.
  Type "?" for a list of Info commands, or "h" to visit an Info tutorial.
  Type "m" to choose a menu item--for instance,
    "mEmacs<Return>" visits the Emacs manual.
  In Emacs Info, you can click mouse button 2 on a menu item
  or cross reference to follow it to its target.
  Each menu line that starts with a * is a topic you can select with "m".
  Every third topic has a red * to help pick the right number to type.

* Menu:

* Info: (info).         How to use the documentation browsing system.

### Emacs ###

* Emacs: (emacs).       The extensible self-documenting text editor.
* Emacs FAQ: (efaq).    Frequently Asked Questions about Emacs.
* Dired-X: (dired-x).   Dired Extra Features.
* Ediff: (ediff).       A visual interface for comparing and merging programs.
* Org Mode: (org).      Outline-based notes management and organizer.

### Lisp ###

* ELisp Intro: (eintr). A simple introduction to Emacs Lisp programming.
* Elisp: (elisp).       The Emacs Lisp Reference Manual.
* CL: (cl).             Partial Common Lisp support for Emacs Lisp.

### Dev Tools ###

* Speedbar: (speedbar). File/Tag summarizing utility.
* Flymake: (flymake).   An on-the-fly syntax checker for Emacs.
* GNU Coding Standards: (standards).

### Programming Languages ###

* CC mode: (ccmode).    Emacs mode for editing C, C++, Objective-C,
                          Java, Pike, and IDL code.
* Ebrowse: (ebrowse).   A C++ class browser for Emacs.
* ECB: (ecb).           Emacs Code Browser
* PHP Mode: (php).	Aaron S. Hawley's PHP Mode 1.5.0.
* nXML Mode: (nxml-mode).

### Communications ###

* ERC: (erc).           Powerful, modular, and extensible IRC client
                          for Emacs.
* Rcirc: (rcirc).       Internet Relay Chat (IRC) client.

* Gnus: (gnus).         The news reader Gnus.
* Newsticker: (newsticker).   A News ticker for Emacs.

* Message: (message).   Mail and news composition mode that goes with Gnus.
* MH-E: (mh-e).         Emacs interface to the MH mail system.
* MIME: (emacs-mime).   Emacs MIME de/composition library.
* SMTP: (smtpmail).     Emacs library for sending mail via SMTP.
* SC: (sc).             Supercite lets you cite parts of messages you're
                          replying to, in flexible ways.
* Sieve: (sieve).       Managing Sieve scripts in Emacs.

### LaTeX ###

* RefTeX: (reftex).     Emacs support for LaTeX cross-references and citations.
* TeXinfo: (texinfo).   TeXinfo
* TeXi2HTML: (texi2html).

### Utilities ###

* PGG: (pgg).           Emacs interface to various PGP implementations.

* Autotype: (autotype). Convenient features for text that you enter frequently
                          in Emacs.
* Calc: (calc).         Advanced desk calculator and mathematical tool.
* Eshell: (eshell).     A command shell implemented in Emacs Lisp.
* EUDC: (eudc).         An Emacs client for directory servers (LDAP, PH).
* Tramp: (tramp).       Transparent Remote (file) Access, Multiple Protocol.
                          Edit remote files via a remote shell (rsh,
                          ssh, telnet).
* URL: (url).           URL loading package.
* Widget: (widget).     The "widget" package used by the Emacs Customization
                          facility.
* WoMan: (woman).       Browse UN*X Manual Pages "Wo (without) Man".

* VIPER: (viper).       The newest Emacs VI-emulation mode.
                          (also, A VI Plan for Emacs Rescue
                           or the VI PERil.)
* GNU Screen: (screen). GNU's terminal manager
* Bash: (bash).                     The GNU Bourne-Again SHell.
* Tar: (tar).		   Making tape (or disk) archives.

### Books ###
* Little Brother: (littlebrother).
                        Little Brother by Cory Doctorow
